This paper discusses the exhaustion of IPv4 address space and its impact on network infrastructure, which falls under the category of computer networks (cs.NI). The paper also touches upon security concerns related to address space management, which could be classified under cryptography and security (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper discusses the evolution of address space management and use patterns, which could be categorized under information theory (cs.IT) and social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper explores possible solutions to address scarcity issues, which could be classified under distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC).
